nosVersion: 1. Do not install previous versions of NCC (such as 1.4.1) on NOS 4.1.3 clusters. NCC 2.0 is not supported on NOS versions other than 4.1.3. [ENG-31582]
2. Acropolis base software 4.5 and later versions are not supported on the Nutanix NX-2000, NX-2050, and Sandy Bridge NX-3000 platforms. NX-3050/NX-3051/NX-3060/NX-3061 are supported.
1. The supported ESXi releases are 5.0 U2 and U3, 5.1 U1 and U3, and 5.5 U1 and U2. ESXi 5.0 is not supported on Acropolis base software 4.5 and later versions.
2. The supported Hyper-V release is Server 2012 R2. Hyper-V requires a 64 GB DOM.
3. Acropolis hypervisor (AHV) support is transparent because it is included automatically as part of the Phoenix ISO.
1. The NX-1020 can be mixed with the NX-1065S if both platforms are using the 1GBase-T interface. NX-1020 nodes cannot be mixed with any other platforms.
2. The maximum cluster size is eight nodes.

3. The NX-1000 series nodes can be mixed with other products in the same cluster only if all the NX-1000 nodes have at least 10 cores per node and all nodes are running 10 GbE networking. If any NX-1000 series node is using the 1 GbE interface, the maximum cluster size is eight nodes. If any NX-1000 nodes are using the 10 GbE interface, the cluster size is the same as for all other platforms. Dedup and compression issupported for all NX-1000 platforms, except the NX-1020.
4. Because it has a larger Flash tier, NX-3050, NX-3060, and NX-3060-G4/-G5 are recommended over other products to be mixed with all NX-6000 series and NX-8150.

5. The NX-8150, NX-8150-G4 and NX-8150-G5 can be mixed with all the systems shown. However, for optimal performance with Microsoft Exchange and Oracle database deployments, the cluster should only contain NX-8150 blocks. You should ensure that you have at least 20 TB failover capacity in an NX-8150 cluster.

6. The storage-heavy NX-6035C and NX-6035C-G5 platforms have unique requirements.
  • Any cluster that contains an NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 node needs to have at least two compute nodes.
  • The NX-6035C and NX-6035C-G5 can run only Nutanix Controller VMs. It can not run guest VMs.
  • Any cluster that contains an NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 node must be sized to tolerate a node failure. The best way to do this is to add an additional NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 node to the cluster. Although this is not a requirement, Nutanix recommends that any cluster that contains any NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 nodes should have at least two NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 nodes.
  • It is possible to create a standalone NX-6035C or NX-6035C-G5 cluster with a minimum of 3 nodes to be used as a replication target for any Nutanix cluster.
  • Mixing the NX-6035C platform with XenServer nodes is not supported.

7. The NX-1065S requires both a 10 GbE NIC and the Intel Xeon E5-2680v2 10-core Ivy Bridge 2.8 GHz CPU to be mixed with other platforms. If the NX-1065S is using the 1 GbE interface, the maximum cluster size is eight nodes.

8. Encrypted drives (SED) cannot be mixed with unencrypted (non-SED) drives in the same node, even if encryption is disabled. Nutanix does not support this configuration. Encrypted nodes can be mixed with unencrypted nodes in the same cluster if encryption was never enabled and remains disabled.

9. Nutanix now allows mixing of all-flash and hybrid SSD/HDD nodes in the same cluster (as of AOS 5.1).
  • A minimum of two all-flash nodes are required in mixed all-flash/hybrid clusters.
  • The minimum number of each node type (all-flash/hybrid) must be equal to the cluster redundancy factor. For example, clusters with a redundancy factor of 2 must have a minimum of 2 hybrid and 2 all-flash nodes.
  • You can run guest VMs on the all-flash nodes in clusters that also have hybrid nodes as long as the cluster includes two or more all-flash nodes.

10. Nutanix now allows mixing of any -G4 and -G5 hybrid nodes in the same cluster unless other exclusions are listed in this matrix (as of AOS 5.1).
  • A minimum of two storage-heavy nodes or two all flash nodes are recommended as part of the mixed hybrid clusters for data redundancy.
  • You can run guest VMs on the all-flash nodes in clusters that also have hybrid nodes as long as the cluster includes two or more all-flash/storage-heavy nodes. If there is only one storage-heavy or one all-flash node in the mixed hybrid cluster, you might not be able to run guest VMs on the all-flash node.
  • For any mixed cluster with ESXi hosts and nodes with different CPU families, ensure that ESXi EVC mode is enabled in the cluster.

11. If you expand a cluster by adding a node with older generation hardware to a cluster that was initially created with later generation hardware, power cycle (do not reboot)  any guest VMs before migrating them to the added older generation node or before upgrading the cluster. Guest VMs are migrated during hypervisor and firmware upgrades (but not AOS upgrades).  For example, if you are adding a node with G4 Haswell CPUs to a cluster that also has newer G5 nodes with Broadwell CPUs, you must power cycle guest VMs hosted on the G5 nodes before you can migrate the VMs to the node with G4 CPUs. Power cycling the guest VMs enables them to discover G4 processor changes.  Power cycle guest VMs from the Prism web console VM dashboard. Do not perform a Guest Reboot; a VM power cycle is required in this case.
1. Please see the Nutanix hypervisor support policy statement in our Support FAQ.
2. Nutanix does not support hypervisor downgrades.

3. Please contact your Hypervisor Vendor for any questions regarding their support policies. Nutanix strongly recommends that customers deploy an 'in-support' version of hypervisor on Nutanix systems.
4. This matrix displays the compatible hypervisor version(s) available for each platform at the time of the selected platform release.
5. The message 'No matching records found' for selected model and hypervisor combinations indicates that the selected model and hypervisor combination are not compatible or QA certified by Nutanix.

6. For AOS 5.1 clusters: Running vSphere 6.5 as a hypervisor host is supported in AOS 5.1 on Nutanix NX platforms except those legacy platforms with 16 GB SATA DOM hypervisor boot drives. Knowledge Base article KB 4397 on the Nutanix support portal describes how to discover the SATA DOM size on your system.

7. Do not deploy ESXi 6.5 on Nutanix clusters running AOS 5.1 if you require or want to configure VMware Fault Tolerance (FT). 
Nutanix Engineering has discovered and is aware of VMware FT compatibility issues in the ESXi 6.5 release, which have been reported to VMware.
8. AOS 5.1 and later versions support ESXi 6.5. ESXi 6.5 is not supported on 5.0.3.x / 4.7.6.x and later versions. AOS 5.1.x / 5.0.3.x / 4.7.6.x and later versions support ESXi 6.5a.
